observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Head of the Procuring Entity direct the:

BAC Secretariat to submit the lacking documents such as the TWG Report on Post-Qualification and related Minutes of the Meeting during BAC meeting, Construction Methods and Statement of Ongoing and Awarded but not yet Started Government and Private Contracts by the Contractor;

TWG to conduct Bid Evaluation and Post Qualification diligently, taking advantage of the maximum time period set in accordance with pertinent provisions of RA 9184 and its IRR; and

We recommended that the LCE direct the Municipal Treasurer (MT) to:

Apply the situs of taxation in the imposition of local business taxes to maximize local revenue generation by the Municipality;



Strictly implement the applicable tax rates provided in the Revenue Code of the Municipality of Tubao and stop using the size of the business establishment as basis in assessing business tax due from taxpayers; and

We therefore recommended that the LCE:
Facilitate the immediate establishment of an Inventory Committee, composed of representatives from the General Services, Accounting and Property/Supply Offices, and concerned End-User Units, to oversee and standardize the inventory-taking process and ensure better coordination between departments moving forward;
Direct the GSO-Designate to:
Lead the immediate conduct of the physical inventory of PPE, in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 and Section 124 of the NGAS Manual, ensuring that results are properly documented in the RPCPPE;
Coordinate with all Offices in the planning and execution of the physical count to ensure accuracy, completeness, and compliance with the inventory procedures prescribed under COA guidelines;
Oversee the identification, and verification of unserviceable PPEs, and ensure that they are reported and disposed of according to COA Circular No. 92-386 and NGAS disposal procedures; and
Investigate and follow up on unlocated properties to ensure that missing items are properly accounted for, and that the necessary documentation such as the IIRUP, is prepared and submitted.
Direct the MA to:
Reconcile the Accounting Office’s records on PPE with those of the GSO, upon completion of the physical count, in accordance with Item 5.12 of COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Initiate the regular updating and maintenance of PLCs and other subsidiary property records to reflect current conditions, locations, and accountability for PPE items;
Ensure that PPE balances presented in the financial statements are based on verified and reconciled inventory records, and that any necessary adjustments are supported by proper documentation; and
Monitor compliance with deadlines for the submission of the RPCPPE and include inventory oversight as part of regular internal control procedures.
After completion of the necessary preparatory steps, we recommended that the LCE initiate the One-Time Cleansing of PPE accounts, in coordination with the Inventory Committee, as required by COA Circular No. 2020-006, to update PPE records by keeping only verified and usable assets and derecognize properties that no longer exist, thereby enhancing the accuracy of the Municipality’s financial reports and strengthen accountability over government property.

We recommended that the LCE direct the AAO/HRMO and MA to:
Reconcile the discrepancies related to current and prior years’ transactions, and effect the necessary adjustments, and promptly remit any outstanding balances;
Coordinate with other responsible offices to ensure immediate updating and regular reconciliation of employee records with GSIS, Pag-IBIG, and PhilHealth, to prevent discrepancies and ensure accurate remittances and benefit eligibility;
Conduct a regular review of the monthly premiums deducted from payroll/disbursement vouchers for remittance to GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth, and ensure that amounts withheld are consistent with the amounts required to be remitted monthly;
For over-the-counter payments, establish a policy requiring the periodic reporting of payments and the submission of proof of payment to the HR/Accounting Office; and
Strictly abide with the provisions of Section 5(c) of RA 8291, Sections 6(a) and 3(e) of Rule VII of IRR of RA No. 9769, and Section 19(d) of Title III Rule III of the Revised IRR of RA 7875, to avoid administrative sanctions.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Bids and Awards Committee to:

Prepare the APP using the format prescribed in Section 4.0 of GPPB Resolution No. 20-2015 dated July 16, 2015 which contains the procurement methods to be adopted, time schedule of the different procurement activities, and sources of funds; 

Ensure that all procurement activities for the incoming year are incorporated in the APP;



Plan the procurement of common-use supplies and goods by consolidating the requirements of the different departments and procuring them through the DBM-PS.  In case of non-availability as certified by the depot, adopt the competitive bidding modality or any of the alternative modes when applicable but subject to proper authorization; and 

Consider procuring Petroleum Fuel, Oil and Lubricant Products through Negotiated Procurement – Direct Retail Purchase in accordance with Section V.D.10 of Annex “H” – Consolidated Guidelines for the Alternative Methods of Procurement of the 2016 revised IRR of RA 9184.

We also recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct all the department heads to religiously prepare and submit the PPMP to aid in the preparation of the prescribed APP.

We recommended that the Head of the Procuring Entity direct the:

BAC Secretariat to submit the lacking documents such as the TWG Report on Post-Qualification and related Minutes of the Meeting during BAC meeting, Construction Methods and Statement of Ongoing and Awarded but not yet Started Government and Private Contracts by the Contractor;

TWG to conduct Bid Evaluation and Post Qualification diligently, taking advantage of the maximum time period set in accordance with pertinent provisions of RA 9184 and its IRR; and


Bids and Awards Committee to:

Remind prospective bidders during the pre-bid conference on the completeness of information in the required Class “A” documents, particularly, the completeness of the declared ongoing and awarded but not yet started government and private contracts and accuracy of the declared NFCC. Otherwise, disqualify non-compliant bidders during bid evaluation or post qualification based on the grounds set under Section 30.1 of the 2016 Revised IRR of RA 9184; and

Secure the additional requirements from the winning bidder before the signing of contract in accordance with Section 37.2 of the2016 revised IRR of RA 9184;

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the LDRRMO and MDPC to prioritize the implementation of LDRRMF to meet the basic needs of its constituents within the community, specifically:

PPAs under Continuing Appropriations shall be implemented immediately at the beginning of the year. In case of discontinuance, the PPAs shall be re-appropriated for more important initiatives; 


Special Trust Funds shall be reviewed at the beginning of the year and its implementation be prioritized the same way with the Continuing Appropriations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Direct the Building Official to a) provide status on those issued building permits without occupancy permits and impose necessary fees for completed projects, and thereafter, monitor those issued with building permits to secure occupancy permits first before actually occupying the structures constructed; 

b.) submit the building permits and occupancy permits issued per month to the Municipal Assessor in order to be used as basis for assessment and updating of the Tax Assessment Roll;

Tap the Barangay Officials to report to the Building Official monthly/quarterly the on-going construction and completed structures in their barangays in order to facilitate the Building Official in monitoring compliance of the structures with the National Building Code of the Philippines and maximize income generated therewith;

Enjoin the Municipal Engineer to religiously monitor newly constructed buildings, whether commercial or residential; and 


Direct the Municipal Assessor to verify whether real properties within the municipality are properly listed in the assessment rolls, specifically those newly constructed or renovated.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer to:

Ensure that only programs, projects, and activities which are incorporated in the approved budget and approved Local DRRM plan are implemented so that planned goals and objectives for the year are guaranteed to be achieved;

Initiate proper authorization process in case there are necessary changes to be made in the originally approved plan by enacting a Sangguniang Bayan Resolution and an Appropriation Ordinance prior to the implementation of PPAs and subsequent disbursement of Local DRRM funds;

Properly schedule the implementation of PPAs by assigning specific dates or shorter time frames with due consideration on the climate of the country; and  

Strictly adhere with the time schedules assigned in the implementation of PPAs.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct all the Department/Office Heads to ensure completeness of information in the authorized Trip Tickets by indicating the following information in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 75-6 dated November 7, 1975 to support the reasonableness of fuel purchased and consumed from official travels:

plate number of vehicle used;
specific address of places to be visited;
time of departure from office/garage;
time of arrival at purpose;
time of departure from place/s to be visited or inspected;
approximate distance travelled to and from;
time of arrival back to office/garage;
balance on tank-issued by office from stock-add-used purchased during to and from;
gear oil issued;
lubricating oil issued;
speed meter reading at beginning of trip-end of trip-distance travelled to and from

